In my opinion, there is a reason for that. Consider the example above, slightly changed:<p><pre><code>    public foo(Bar bar) {
        bar = baz(bar);
        //Lots (10+ lines) of code.
        bar = qux(bar);
        //Lots (10+ lines) of code.
        return finishProcess(bar);  
    }
</code></pre>
It is hard to spot the second reuse of variable <i>bar</i>. This can make code harder to understand; it&#x27;s a lot easier to just look at the point of definition of a variable and assume it never changes. At least, that is why I tend to use <i>final</i> when writing Java, and <i>val</i> when writing Scala.<p>Of course, usually when adding <i>final</i> to messy Java code I&#x27;m trying to understand, this ends up telling me that the whole piece of code was fragile, hard to understand and in dire need of a refactoring. All of which makes <i>final</i> useful to me.
